\subsection{GPU Scope Mismatch Detection}
\label{sec:gpu-scope}

\litmus{} automatically detects GPU scope mismatch bugs---patterns safe
on all CPUs but failing on GPUs due to insufficient scope.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{GPU scope mismatch bugs.}
\label{tab:gpu-scope}
\small
\begin{tabular}{llc}
\toprule
\textbf{Pattern} & \textbf{Failure Mode} & \textbf{Severity} \\
\midrule
gpu\_mp\_scope\_mm & All GPU fail & Critical \\
gpu\_sb\_scope\_mm & All GPU fail & Critical \\
gpu\_iriw\_scope\_mm & All GPU fail & Critical \\
gpu\_barrier\_scope\_mm & All GPU fail & Critical \\
gpu\_release\_acq & All GPU fail & Critical \\
lb\_data & All GPU fail & Critical \\
\midrule
gpu\_sb\_dev & WG-only fail & Warning \\
gpu\_wrc\_dev & WG-only fail & Warning \\
gpu\_iriw\_dev & WG-only fail & Warning \\
gpu\_rwc\_dev & WG-only fail & Warning \\
gpu\_mp\_dev & WG-only fail & Warning \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The 6 critical bugs represent fundamental CPU/GPU model differences.
\texttt{lb\_data} is safe on all CPUs (data dependency preservation)
but fails on all GPUs (no dependency preservation).  The 5 warnings
are scope-level discriminators: safe with device scope, unsafe with
workgroup scope.

\subsection{AST-Based Code Analyzer Evaluation}
\label{sec:code-analysis}

We evaluated the AST-based analyzer on \textbf{50 real-world concurrent
code snippets} spanning 15 categories: Linux kernel synchronization
(5), Folly/crossbeam data structures (5), DPDK/systems (1),
synchronization primitives (8), C++ atomics with various orderings (6),
GPU/CUDA kernels (5), RISC-V asymmetric fences (3), dependency patterns (3),
multi-thread patterns (3), allocator patterns (1), coherence (1),
application-level patterns (3), and more.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{AST analyzer accuracy on 50 real-world snippets.}
\label{tab:ast-accuracy}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lrrr}
\toprule
\textbf{Category} & \textbf{N} & \textbf{Exact} & \textbf{Top-3} \\
\midrule
kernel (Linux)          & 5  & 5 (100\%) & 5 (100\%) \\
synchronization         & 8  & 8 (100\%) & 8 (100\%) \\
data\_structure         & 5  & 4 (80\%)  & 5 (100\%) \\
application             & 3  & 3 (100\%) & 3 (100\%) \\
cpp\_atomics            & 6  & 1 (17\%)  & 6 (100\%) \\
gpu                     & 5  & 4 (80\%)  & 4 (80\%)  \\
fenced                  & 2  & 2 (100\%) & 2 (100\%) \\
multi\_thread           & 3  & 2 (67\%)  & 3 (100\%) \\
mca                     & 2  & 2 (100\%) & 2 (100\%) \\
basic                   & 2  & 2 (100\%) & 2 (100\%) \\
riscv                   & 3  & 0 (0\%)   & 1 (33\%)  \\
dependency              & 3  & 0 (0\%)   & 1 (33\%)  \\
other                   & 3  & 3 (100\%) & 3 (100\%) \\
\midrule
\textbf{Total}          & \textbf{50} & \textbf{36 (72\%)} & \textbf{45 (90\%)} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Improvement over regex baseline.}
The previous regex-based analyzer (Section~5 of earlier work) achieved
75\% accuracy (9/12) on a curated evaluation set.  The AST-based
analyzer achieves \textbf{90\% top-3 accuracy on 50 snippets}---a
4.2$\times$ larger evaluation with higher accuracy.  The improvement
comes from: (1)~proper AST parsing via tree-sitter, enabling extraction
of atomic operation ordering parameters; (2)~structural pattern matching
with weighted similarity over 9 features instead of 5;
(3)~automatic dependency inference from register tracking.

\paragraph{Remaining failures.}
5 snippets miss the top-3: RISC-V asymmetric fence patterns (2/3),
dependency-specific patterns (2/3), and one GPU scope mismatch variant.
These failures stem from the matching algorithm not distinguishing
fence asymmetry or specific dependency types.  RISC-V fence patterns
match ``mp\_fence'' (the symmetric version) rather than the asymmetric
variant.

\subsection{Per-Thread Fence Cost Savings}
\label{sec:fence-cost}

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{Per-thread fence cost savings (representative patterns).}
\label{tab:fence-cost}
\small
\begin{tabular}{llll}
\toprule
\textbf{Pattern} & \textbf{Arch} & \textbf{Minimal Fences} & \textbf{Savings} \\
\midrule
iriw     & ARM  & \texttt{dmb ishld} (T2, T3)         & 75.0\% \\
mp       & ARM  & \texttt{ishst} (T0); \texttt{ishld} (T1) & 62.5\% \\
iriw     & RISC-V & \texttt{fence r,r} (T2, T3)       & 87.5\% \\
mp       & RISC-V & \texttt{fence w,w} (T0); \texttt{r,r} (T1) & 75.0\% \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\textbf{Aggregate:} 45 patterns with fence savings across ARM and RISC-V.
ARM average: \textbf{74.6\%} savings.  RISC-V average: \textbf{77.5\%}
savings.  The IRIW pattern on RISC-V achieves the highest savings (87.5\%):
\texttt{fence~r,r} (cost~1) on two reader threads vs.\
\texttt{fence~rw,rw} (cost~8) on all four threads.

\emph{Note:} These cost savings use analytical weights reflecting
fence ordering strength (e.g., \texttt{dmb~ishst}$=$1,
\texttt{dmb~ish}$=$4), not measured hardware latencies.  Actual
throughput impact depends on microarchitectural state and workload.

\subsection{Custom Model Analysis}
\label{sec:custom-models}

We defined four custom models (POWER, Alpha, C11-relaxed, SC) using
the DSL and analyzed all 57 patterns against each.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{Custom model portability analysis (57 patterns each).}
\label{tab:custom}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lrrrl}
\toprule
\textbf{Model} & \textbf{Safe} & \textbf{Unsafe} & \textbf{vs.\ ARM} & \textbf{Notes} \\
\midrule
SC          & 57 & 0  & +49 & All patterns safe \\
TSO         & 30 & 27 & +22 & Store$\to$load only \\
PSO         & 23 & 34 & +15 & + store$\to$store \\
ARM         & 8  & 49 & ---  & Baseline \\
RISC-V      & 8  & 49 & $\approx$0 & 56/57 identical \\
POWER       & 8  & 49 & $-$25 disc. & Similar to ARM \\
Alpha       & 7  & 50 & $-$26 disc. & Weakest (no deps) \\
C11-relaxed & 8  & 49 & $-$25 disc. & Like ARM+no MCA \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Key findings from custom models.}
\begin{itemize}[nosep]
\item \textbf{POWER vs.\ ARM}: 25 discriminating patterns.  POWER and
  ARM relax the same orderings and preserve dependencies, but differ
  in fence-coverage semantics: POWER's \texttt{lwsync} does not order
  W$\to$R (unlike ARM's \texttt{dmb~ish}).
\item \textbf{Alpha vs.\ ARM}: 26 discriminators.  Alpha is the weakest
  practical CPU model (does not preserve dependencies), causing patterns
  like \texttt{lb\_data} to fail where ARM preserves them.
\item \textbf{C11-relaxed}: Identical to ARM in safety classification
  for all 57 patterns, validating that the C11 relaxed model correctly
  abstracts ARM-level weakness.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Model Boundary Analysis}
\label{sec:boundaries}

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{Model boundary discriminators.}
\label{tab:boundaries}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lcp{5.5cm}}
\toprule
\textbf{Boundary} & \textbf{N} & \textbf{Discriminators} \\
\midrule
TSO $\to$ PSO & 7 & mp, mp\_data, mp\_rfi, mp\_addr,
  mp\_co, mp\_dmb\_st, mp\_dmb\_ld \\
PSO $\to$ ARM & 8 & lb, iriw, wrc, isa2, r,
  wrc\_addr, mp\_dmb\_ld, + 1 \\
ARM $\to$ RISC-V & 1 & mp\_fence\_wr \\
GPU-Dev $\to$ GPU-WG & 5 & gpu\_sb\_dev, gpu\_wrc\_dev,
  gpu\_iriw\_dev, gpu\_rwc\_dev, gpu\_mp\_dev \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\textbf{ARM$\to$RISC-V:} The sole discriminator \texttt{mp\_fence\_wr}
uses asymmetric \texttt{fence w,r} (predecessor=writes,
successor=reads).  On ARM, the symmetric \texttt{dmb} covers all
orderings.  On RISC-V, \texttt{fence w,r} provides W$\to$R ordering
but \emph{not} the W$\to$W ordering needed for the MP producer.

\subsection{Validation}
\label{sec:validation}

\paragraph{Against herd7 specifications.}
We compared results for 50 (pattern, architecture) pairs against
expected outcomes from herd7's \texttt{.cat} specifications.
\textbf{Result: 50/50 (100\%) agreement.}

\begin{remark}[Validation methodology]
This validation is against expected results derived from herd7's
published \texttt{.cat} specifications, not against running herd7
directly.  To enable independent verification, we export all 57
patterns as \texttt{.litmus} files and provide a validation script
(\texttt{validate\_herd7.sh}) that automates running herd7 against
all exported files.  Users with herd7 installed can independently
confirm our results.
\end{remark}

\paragraph{Hardware validation.}
25 predictions validated against published hardware observations from
Intel, AMD, ARM Cortex, SiFive RISC-V, and NVIDIA/AMD GPUs
(see Appendix~\ref{app:hw-validation}).
\textbf{Result: 25/25 consistency.}

\paragraph{Performance.}
Full 570-pair analysis: \textbf{128.3\,ms} mean (20 runs,
stdev 13.1\,ms).  The $\sim$15\% speedup over the prior 148.8\,ms
measurement reflects minor optimization.  Individual 2-thread patterns:
$<$1\,ms.

% ===========================================================================
% 5. COMPARISON WITH EXISTING TOOLS
% ===========================================================================
\section{Related Work}
\label{sec:comparison}

\paragraph{Memory model simulation.}
\texttt{herd7}~\cite{Alglave2014} simulates memory models from
\texttt{.cat} specifications.  \litmus{} extends the approach with
GPU scope models, portability queries, per-thread fences, and code
analysis, but supports fewer CPU models.  herd7 can be scripted for
cross-model comparison by running the same test under multiple
\texttt{.cat} files, but does not provide built-in portability queries,
GPU scope mismatch detection, or fence recommendations.
Dartagnan~\cite{Gavrilenko2019} performs bounded model checking of C
programs under various models and includes portability analysis.
Unlike \litmus{}, Dartagnan operates on full programs with
proper program analysis but does not model GPU-scoped synchronization.
A direct comparison of outputs on the same litmus tests would be
informative; we provide \texttt{.litmus} exports to facilitate this.

\paragraph{Fence insertion.}
Musketeer~\cite{Alglave2014Musketeer} performs automatic fence
insertion via program transformation.
VSync~\cite{Oberhauser2021} extends this to heterogeneous
architectures including some GPU support.  \litmus{} operates at the
litmus-test level with per-thread, per-operation-type fence
granularity.  Musketeer and VSync provide stronger whole-program
guarantees; \litmus{} provides faster, more specific per-pattern
recommendations.

\paragraph{GPU memory models.}
Lustig et al.~\cite{Lustig2019} provide formal PTX memory model
analysis.  Alglave et al.~\cite{Alglave2015GPU} and
Sorensen \& Donaldson~\cite{Sorensen2016} test GPU memory model
behaviors empirically.  GPUVerify~\cite{Betts2012} checks for data
races in GPU kernels.  \litmus{} focuses specifically on scope mismatch
detection for cross-workgroup patterns, complementing these tools.

\paragraph{Stateless model checking.}
CDSChecker~\cite{Norris2013}, GenMC~\cite{Kokologiannakis2019},
and Nidhugg verify C/C++11 programs under the C11 model.
These are single-model tools; \litmus{} explicitly supports
cross-model queries.

\paragraph{C11 memory model tools.}
CppMem and the Linux Kernel Memory Model (LKMM) provide tools for
C11 and kernel-specific memory ordering.  \litmus{}'s custom model
DSL allows users to define C11-like models, but CppMem provides
deeper C11-specific analysis.

