% ===========================================================================
% 6. DISCUSSION
% ===========================================================================
\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

\paragraph{Scope and limitations.}
\litmus{} operates on litmus test patterns (57 built-in), not arbitrary
programs.  The AST-based code analyzer bridges this gap with 90\%
top-3 accuracy on 50 real-world snippets, but cannot handle complex
control flow, indirect memory access, or template-heavy C++ code.
Dependencies are manually annotated in pattern definitions, not inferred
from arbitrary programs.

\paragraph{Fence cost model.}
Fence costs are analytical weights (e.g., \texttt{dmb ishst}$=$1,
\texttt{dmb ish}$=$4) reflecting ordering strength, not measured
hardware latencies.  Real fence costs depend on microarchitectural
state, pipeline effects, and workload.  The savings percentages indicate
\emph{ordering strength reduction}, not guaranteed throughput improvement.

\paragraph{GPU model simplification.}
Our 6 GPU models treat OpenCL, Vulkan, and PTX as differing primarily
in scope level.  In reality, these APIs have different semantics (e.g.,
Vulkan's availability/visibility operations, PTX's \texttt{.weak}
modifiers).  Our models capture the core scope mismatch phenomenon
but not all API-specific subtleties.

\paragraph{Conservative overapproximation.}
The tool is conservative: it may report false positives but not false
negatives.  LB on ARM/RISC-V is marked ``Allowed'' (sound
overapproximation); the forbidden outcome requires out-of-thin-air
values that are rarely observable.  Of 25 hardware validation points,
3 showed conservative overapproximation (tool predicted unsafe,
outcome not observed on tested hardware).

\paragraph{Custom model limitations.}
The DSL captures the core aspects of memory models (relaxed orderings,
fences, dependencies) but does not support the full expressiveness of
herd7's \texttt{.cat} language.  Complex model features like partial
orders over coherence, forwarding semantics, and operational model
constructs are not representable.

\paragraph{Validation completeness.}
Our validation against herd7 uses expected values from published
\texttt{.cat} specifications, not direct herd7 invocation.  We mitigate
this by providing \texttt{.litmus} exports for independent verification.
A full automated comparison against herd7 and Dartagnan would strengthen
validation; we view this as important future work.

% ===========================================================================
% 7. CONCLUSION
% ===========================================================================
\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

We presented \litmus{}, a cross-architecture portability checker that
addresses a practical gap in the concurrency verification toolchain.
The tool analyzes 57 litmus patterns across 10 architectures in under
130\,ms, supports user-defined custom models via a lightweight DSL,
provides AST-based code analysis with 90\% top-3 accuracy on 50
real-world snippets, and detects 11 GPU scope mismatch bugs invisible
to CPU-only tools.  Per-thread minimal fence recommendations achieve
75--78\% average cost savings, and all results are validated against
herd7 specifications (50/50) and published hardware observations (25/25).
Exported \texttt{.litmus} files enable independent verification.

